==English==

===Etymology===
Middle English [[scharp]], from Old English [[scearp]].  Therefore of [[Germanic]] origin, e.g. it is akin to the [[German]] [[scharf]]. It is also akin to words which have the sense of scraping, e.g. Latin [[scrobis]] '[[ditch]]', Russian skresti 'to [[scrape]]'.

===Pronunciations===
*[[w:General American|GenAm]] /ʃɑɹp/
*[[w:Received Pronunciation|RP]] /ʃɑːp/

===Adjective===
'''sharp'''  ({{compar}}: '''[[sharper]]''', {{superl}}: '''[[sharpest]]''')

# Having the ability to cut easily.
# Intelligent.
# Having the ability to pierce easily.
# {{music}} A note that is played a [[semitone]] higher than usual (denoted by the name of the note followed by the symbol &#9839;).
# {{music}} The scale having a particular sharp note as its [[tonic]].
#: ''The Moonlight Sonata is written in C&#9839; minor (C sharp minor.)''
# ''Music'' Higher-pitched than desired.
#:''The oboe was an eighth of a tone '''sharp'''.''
# Having an intense flavour, as '''''sharp''' cheddar.''
# Intense and sudden, as ''a '''sharp''' pain.''
# Illegal or dishonest, as ''a '''sharp''' practice.''
# Exactly.
#:''I'll see you at twelve o'clock, '''sharp'''.''

